title: For Sale:  Czech VZ98/22 (K98)
postcontent: This is a Czech built version of the German WWI K98 Mauser. After WWI the Czech's took one of Germany's Mauser lines as reparations for WWI and began producing the Mauser. This one was built in 1922 hence 98/22. After the Czech's modernized to a newer version (98/24) they sold the earlier versions to Turkey hence the newer sight using Arabic numbers and the bolt safety with the Turkish crescent stamped into the left side. This rifle has a beautiful bore and presents itself well. Nice stock without cracks. It has pitting along where the wood and metal meet. Have fired it, fires well and uses 8mm Mauser ammo.

postcontent: Nice French lebel carbine. The bore is great and shot really well last time I had it out. Has a small crack in the top handguard on the left side. No cracks in the stock.Comes with an original 3 round clip which are extremely difficult to find. Most out there are reproductions. These are $30+ dollars.  You don't need it to shoot the gun but its nice to have. Im also including the following ammo: 2 tracers, 2 armor piercing, 2 standard ball and 2 duds that didn't go off.I have new brass, bullets and dies I can add to the trade also if wanted.Looking to trade for another gun. Open to ALL gun offers.Older, newer, military surplus, concealed carry guns, ectCall/text Tyler anytime REDACTEDMy buddy who collects these (he has 8) sent me this little history lesson:Your carbine was likely built on a 1890 receiver. It is outfitted with a later style 1892 stock (it has no clearing rod on the left side and has the side bar sling attachment). Originally, an 1890 would have thin sights, which were later updated to the larger "block" sights. In 1916, the 5 shot magazines and handcuffs were added to existing 1892 carbines. These are French designated "Artillery Carbine 1892 modified 1916" (irrelevant to how the receiver is marked). In 1927, your carbine would have had its stock replaced/repaired to have its clearing rod removed and the channel in which it sat filled, and the front barrel band replaced with one that had a stacking quillion. In 1932, you carbine had its chamber reamed out to accept Balle N ammunition.
